'''Alexsey Alekseyevich Belan''' (born 27 June 1987) is a Latvian [[hacker]] on the [[FBI Most Wanted]] list and sanctioned for "malicious cyber-enabled activities" threatening the national security of the United States.<ref name="OFAC">{{cite news |title=Issuance of Amended Executive Order 13694; Cyber-Related Sanctions Designations |publisher=[[United States Department of the Treasury]] |date=December 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229210346/https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20161229.aspx |archive-date=December 29, 2016 |quote=BELAN, Aleksey Alekseyevich (a.k.a. Abyr Valgov; a.k.a. BELAN, Aleksei; a.k.a. BELAN, Aleksey Alexseyevich; a.k.a. BELAN, Alexsei; a.k.a. BELAN, Alexsey; a.k.a. "Abyrvaig"; a.k.a. "Abyrvalg"; a.k.a. "Anthony Anthony"; a.k.a. "Fedyunya"; a.k.a. "M4G"; a.k.a. "Mag"; a.k.a. "Mage"; a.k.a. "Magg"; a.k.a. "Moy.Yawik"; a.k.a. "Mrmagister"), 21 Karyakina St., Apartment 205, Krasnodar, Russia; DOB 27 Jun 1987; POB Riga, Latvia; nationality Latvia; Passport RU0313455106 (Russia); alt. Passport 0307609477 (Russia) (individual) [CYBER2]. |url=https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20161229.aspx |author=[[Office of Foreign Assets Control]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=White House announces retaliation against Russia: Sanctions, ejecting diplomats |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/12/29/politics/russia-sanctions-announced-by-white-house/ |publisher=[[CNN]] |first1=Evan |last1=Perez |first2=Daniella |last2=Diaz |date=December 29, 2016 |quote=Two of the individuals on the sanctions list, Evgeniy Mikhailovich Bogachev and Alexey Belan, are on the FBI wanted list as well. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229222313/http://www.cnn.com/2016/12/29/politics/russia-sanctions-announced-by-white-house/ |archive-date=December 29, 2016}}</ref>
Belan is accused of having stolen consumer data from e-commerce websites in [[Nevada]] and [[California]], and selling that data on the underground market, according to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigations]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Russian-consul-general-in-SF-calls-expulsions-10827338.php |publisher=''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' |title=Russian consul general in SF calls expulsions ‘not human’ |first=Kimberly |last=Veklerov |date=December 30, 2016 |quote=According to the FBI, one of the two, Alexsey Belan, has an open fraud case in the San Francisco office of the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of California|U.S. District Court of Northern California]]. He allegedly hacked into three major e-commerce companies based in California and Nevada in 2012 and 2013. Federal investigators accused Belan of stealing user databases and millions of encrypted passwords. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231163538/http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Russian-consul-general-in-SF-calls-expulsions-10827338.php |archive-date=December 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |quote=Belan stole consumer data in 2012 and 2013 from three e-commerce sites in Nevada and California, sites the FBI declined to name. He's now selling that data to other criminals, Stangl said. |publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2015/06/30/the-fbi-is-willing-to-pay-4-2-million-to-get-these-hackers/ |first=Jacob |last=Bogage |title=The FBI is willing to pay $4.2 million to get these hackers |date=June 30, 2015 |accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name="FBI" /> These accusations include Belan's role in the [[Yahoo! data breaches#Late 2014 breach|2014 Yahoo! data breach]] that affected 500 million user accounts.<ref name="reuters baratov">{{cite web | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yahoo-cyber/canadian-charged-in-yahoo-hacking-case-to-plead-guilty-in-u-s-idUSKBN1DO2PJ | tit