[[Image:Mose ben Sem Tob.jpg|thumb|right|Statue of Moshe in [[Guadalajara, Spain]].]]
[[Image:Zohar.png|thumb|Title page of first edition of the Zohar, Mantua, 1558. [[Library of Congress]].]]
{{wikisourcepar|Chapters on Jewish Literature/Chapter XVII: The Zohar and Later Mysticism|The Zohar and Later Mysticism}}
'''Moses de León''' (c. 1240 &ndash; 1305), known in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] as '''Moshe ben Shem-Tov''' ({{Hebrew|משה בן שם-טוב די-ליאון}}), was a [[History of the Jews in Spain|Spanish]] [[rabbi]] and [[Kabbalist]] who is considered the composer or redactor of the [[Zohar]]. It is a matter of controversy<ref name="jewcyclo">[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/9767-leon-moses-ben-shem-tob-de ''The Jewish Encyclopedia'']</ref> if the Zohar is his own work, or if he committed traditions going back to Rabbi [[Shimon bar Yohai]] in writing. His other works include ''Sefer ha-Rimon'', written in Hebrew.

==Life==
He was born in [[León, Spain]], [[Kingdom of León]], then united with the [[Crown of Castile]].<ref name="jewcyclo" /> He might have been born in [[Guadalajara, Spain|Guadalajara]] and his surname, then, comes from his father, Shem-Tov de León. He spent 30 years in Guadalajara and [[Valladolid]] before moving to [[Ávila, Spain|Ávila]], where he spent the rest of his life. He died at [[Arévalo]] in 1305 while returning to his home.

